Capstone: Loan Default Prediction¶

Problem Overview¶

The bank wants to improve its loan approval process by predicting customers likely to default on home equity loans. A machine learning model must be developed to automate this process, ensuring it is free from biases and interpretable enough for regulatory purposes.

Project Objectives:

  • Build a classification model to predict loan defaults.
  • Identify key factors influencing loan defaults.
  • Ensure the model is interpretable for decision-making.
  • Provide recommendations for improving the loan approval process.
  • Ensure fairness and compliance with regulatory guidelines.

# Plots boxplots and histograms for numerical features of a DataFrame.
def plot_numerical(dataframe, target_variable=None):

    # Extract numerical variables
    if target_variable:
        numeric_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).drop(target_variable, axis=1).columns
    else:
        numeric_columns = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns
    num_vars = len(numeric_columns)

    # Calculate the number of rows for the subplot
    num_rows = (num_vars // 4) + (1 if num_vars % 4 != 0 else 0)

    # Set up the matplotlib figure
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2 * num_rows, 4, figsize=(20, 4 * num_rows * 1.25), constrained_layout=True, gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': [1, 4] * num_rows})

    # Loop through the numerical variables to create boxplots and histograms
    for i, column in enumerate(numeric_columns):
        # Define the row and column index in the subplot grid
        row = (i // 4) * 2
        col = i % 4

        # Create a boxplot for the variable
        sns.boxplot(data=dataframe, x=column, ax=axes[row, col])
        axes[row, col].set_title(f'Box Plot and Histogram for {column}', fontsize=12)
        axes[row, col].tick_params(labelbottom=False)  # Remove x-ticks for the boxplot
        axes[row, col].set_xlabel('')  # Remove x-axis label for the boxplot

        # Create a histogram for the variable
        sns.histplot(data=dataframe, x=column, kde=True, ax=axes[row + 1, col], binwidth=None)
        axes[row + 1, col].set_title('')  # Remove title for the histogram
        axes[row + 1, col].set_xlabel(f'{column}\n\n')  # Set x-axis label for the histogram

    # Remove the excess axes
    i += 1
    delrow =  (i // 4) * 2
    delcol = i % 4
    fig.delaxes(axes[delrow, delcol])
    fig.delaxes(axes[delrow, delcol + 1])
    fig.delaxes(axes[delrow + 1, delcol])
    fig.delaxes(axes[delrow + 1, delcol + 1])

    plt.show()

# Display bar plots for categorical features
def plot_categorical_bars(data):
    """
    Plots bar plots for all categorical columns in the DataFrame.

    Parameters:
        data (DataFrame): The pandas DataFrame containing the data.
    """
    # Identify categorical columns: Either by dtype 'object' or by checking the number of unique values
    categorical_columns = [col for col in data.columns if data[col].dtype == 'object']

    # Set the number of columns for subplot grid
    ncols = 2 if len(categorical_columns) > 2 else len(categorical_columns)
    nrows = (len(categorical_columns) + ncols - 1) // ncols  # Calculate the number of rows needed

    # Set dynamic width of the figure based on the number of columns
    fig_width = 20  # Each subplot approx 5 inches wide
    fig_height = 8 * nrows  # Each subplot approx 5 inches tall

    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows, ncols=ncols, figsize=(fig_width, fig_height))
    axes = axes.flatten() if nrows > 1 or ncols > 1 else [axes]  # Handle the case of a single subplot

    # Loop over the categorical columns and create a bar plot for each
    for i, col in enumerate(categorical_columns):
        sns.countplot(x=col, data=data, ax=axes[i])
        axes[i].set_title(f'Bar Plot of {col}', fontsize=12)
        axes[i].set_xlabel('')
        axes[i].set_ylabel('Count')
        axes[i].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)  # Rotate x-axis labels

    # Hide unused subplots if any
    for j in range(i + 1, len(axes)):
        axes[j].set_visible(False)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Use Top 10 correlated features to target column (Default), evaluate each with the target column
def plot_boxplots(features_df, target_series):
    """
    Parameters:
    - features_df: pandas DataFrame containing the numerical features
    - target_series: pandas Series containing the target variable
    """
    # Get column names of the features
    numeric_cols = features_df.columns

    # Number of numerical features
    num_features = len(numeric_cols)
    num_rows = (num_features + 3) // 3  # Calculate the number of rows needed for subplots

    # Set the figure size based on the number of rows
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 5 * num_rows))

    # Loop through each numerical column and create a boxplot against the target variable
    for i, col in enumerate(numeric_cols, 1):
        plt.subplot(num_rows, 3, i)
        sns.boxplot(x=target_series, y=features_df[col])
        plt.title(f'{col} vs Default (Target)', fontsize=12)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Use Top 10 categorical features to evaluate each with the target column (Default)
def plot_stacked_barcharts(features_df, target_series):
    """
    Parameters:
    - features_df: pandas DataFrame containing the categorical features
    - target_series: pandas Series containing the target variable
    """
    # Get column names of the categorical features
    categorical_cols = features_df.columns

    # Create a gradient colormap from white to steelblue
    steelblue_gradient = LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list("steelblue_gradient", ['lightsteelblue', 'steelblue'])

    # Number of categorical features
    num_features = len(categorical_cols)
    num_rows = (num_features + 2) // 3  # Calculate the number of rows needed for subplots (3 per row)

    # Set the figure size based on the number of rows
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 5 * num_rows))

    # Loop through each categorical column and create a stacked bar chart against the target variable
    for i, col in enumerate(categorical_cols, 1):
        plt.subplot(num_rows, 3, i)

        # Create a crosstab for the relationship between the categorical feature and the target
        crosstab = pd.crosstab(features_df[col], target_series)

        # Plot the stacked bar chart
        crosstab.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=plt.gca(), colormap=steelblue_gradient)

        # Set title and labels
        plt.title(f'{col} vs Default (Target)', fontsize=12)
        plt.ylabel('Proportion')
        plt.xlabel(col)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Generate a correlation matrix for numerical features
def plot_correlation_heatmap(data):
    # Filter out only numerical columns
    numeric_data = data.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64'])

    # Calculate the correlation matrix
    corr_matrix = numeric_data.corr()

    # Create the heatmap
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt='.2f', linewidths=0.5)

    # Add a title
    plt.title('Correlation Heatmap', fontsize=16)

    # Display the plot
    plt.show()

# Function to calculate VIF for numerical features
def calculate_vif(data):
    # Filter out only numerical columns
    numeric_data = data.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).dropna()

    # Add a constant for the regression model
    X = numeric_data.assign(const=1)

    # Create an empty DataFrame to store VIF values
    vif_data = pd.DataFrame()
    vif_data['Feature'] = X.columns

    # Calculate VIF for each feature
    vif_data['VIF'] = [variance_inflation_factor(X.values, i) for i in range(X.shape[1])]

    # Return VIF excluding the constant term
    return vif_data[vif_data['Feature'] != 'const']

EDA Summary and Key Insights¶

The analysis highlighted significant patterns in both numerical and categorical features, offering a clearer understanding of loan default risk.

  • Numerical Features:

    • Higher loan amounts, mortgage dues, and debt-to-income ratios are linked to higher default risk.
    • Shorter job tenure and a higher number of derogatory reports or delinquencies increase default likelihood.
    • Most features have mild skewness, with a few notable outliers, especially in loan and debt-related variables.

  • Categorical Features:

    • Applicants applying for debt consolidation are more likely to default than those applying for home improvement loans.
    • Undefined job categories (classified as "Other") show a higher default rate compared to specific roles like Manager or Office jobs.

  • Feature Correlations:

    • There is a strong correlation between property value and mortgage dues, suggesting a relationship between higher-value properties and larger mortgages.
    • No major multicollinearity issues were found, though MORTDUE and VALUE exhibit a moderate correlation.

Conclusion: Key predictors for loan default risk are larger loan amounts, higher debt-to-income ratios, and poor credit history, while categorical variables like loan purpose and job type also provide valuable insights into default risk. The data is largely clean and ready for modeling, with minimal concerns around multicollinearity.

# Imputes missing values for both training and testing datasets using KNN for numerical features and SimpleImputer (most frequent) for categorical features.
def impute_missing_values_knn(dataframe):
    """
    Parameters:
    - dataframe: DataFrame.

    Returns:
    - dataframe_imputed: Imputed data set (pandas DataFrame).
    """

    # Separate numerical and categorical columns in the training data
    numerical_cols = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64']).columns
    categorical_cols = dataframe.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns

    # Imputation for numerical columns using KNN (fit on X_train, transform on both)
    knn_imputer = KNNImputer(n_neighbors=5)
    dataframe[numerical_cols] = knn_imputer.fit_transform(dataframe[numerical_cols])

    # Imputation for categorical columns using most frequent (fit on X_train, transform on both)
    cat_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')
    dataframe[categorical_cols] = cat_imputer.fit_transform(dataframe[categorical_cols])

    return dataframe

# Function to treat outliers for each column with outliers, excluding target column
def treat_outliers(df, exclude_columns):
    """
    Parameters:
    - df: pandas DataFrame
    - exclude_columns: list of columns to exclude from the outlier treatment.

    Returns:
    - DataFrame with outliers treated for the specified numerical columns.
    """
    # Exclude specified columns from outlier treatment
    numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['number']).columns.difference(exclude_columns)

    for column in numeric_cols:
        Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1

        # Define the lower and upper bounds for outliers
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

        # Replace lower outliers with the lower bound and upper outliers with the upper bound
        df[column] = df[column].apply(lambda x: lower_bound if x < lower_bound else (upper_bound if x > upper_bound else x))

    return df

# Encodes categorical features in the DataFrame using one-hot encoding.
def encode_categorical(df):
    """
    Parameters:
    - df: DataFrame containing the features.

    Returns:
    - DataFrame with categorical features one-hot encoded.
    """
    # Select categorical columns
    categorical_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns

    # Apply one-hot encoding
    df_encoded = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=categorical_cols, drop_first=True)

    # Convert only boolean columns to integers (1/0)
    for col in df_encoded.columns:
        if df_encoded[col].dtype == 'bool':
            df_encoded[col] = df_encoded[col].astype(int)

    return df_encoded

Missing Value Imputation¶

Reasons for Choosing Imputation Methods:

  • KNN Imputation (Numerical Data): Accounts for relationships between variables like loan amounts and debt-to-income ratios, leveraging patterns in similar rows.
  • Most Frequent Value (Categorical Data): Replaces missing values with the most common category, which is reasonable for features like REASON and JOB.

Outlier Treatment¶

Outlier treatment is essential to prevent extreme values from distorting model performance, especially in financial data. The following code uses IQR-based outlier treatment to cap outliers within acceptable limits.

  • No Outlier Treatment for DEROG, DELINQ, and NINQ due to their discrete nature.
  • Identifying Outliers: The interquartile range (IQR) method calculates the range between the 25th and 75th percentiles, defining outliers as values outside this range.
  • Setting Bounds: The lower and upper bounds are set at 1.5 times the IQR below Q1 and above Q3, respectively.
  • Capping Values: Outliers below the lower bound are replaced by the lower bound, and those above the upper bound are capped at the upper limit.
  • Excluding Target Variable: The target variable is excluded from outlier treatment to avoid impacting the response variable.

Model Building Approach¶

In this phase, we will focus on building both linear and ensemble models to predict loan defaults, utilizing the preprocessed data. Here's the detailed approach:

Linear Models (on Scaled Datasets):

  • Logistic Regression: We'll build this model after removing insignificant features based on statistical tests (like p-values) to improve model efficiency.
  • Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA): Similar to logistic regression, LDA will be built after feature selection to improve interpretability and ensure robust classification.

Ensemble Methods:

  • Random Forest: We'll first build a basic Random Forest model, followed by hyperparameter tuning to optimize performance using techniques like grid search or random search.
  • ADA Boost: We will build an Adaptive Boosting (ADA Boost) model and fine-tune its parameters to improve model performance.
  • Gradient Boosting: This model will be trained and then optimized through hyperparameter tuning to enhance its ability to handle complex decision boundaries.
  • XGBoost: We'll start with the default XGBoost model and tune its hyperparameters to improve its predictive power and speed.

Benefits of this Approach:

  • Linear Models: These provide easy interpretability and are useful for understanding the importance of features, especially after removing insignificant variables.
  • Ensemble Methods: These models are more flexible, can handle feature interactions better, and are less prone to overfitting due to techniques like bagging and boosting. Hyperparameter tuning will further enhance their performance.

Evaluating Model Performance¶

Performance Metric Check and Model Selection:

  • After training all models, we will evaluate them using performance metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and AUC-ROC to determine the best-performing model. We will compare the results, focusing on both predictive accuracy and the model's ability to generalize. The model with the best balance between performance and interpretability will be selected as the final model.
  • We will also attempt to estimate how much each model contributes in terms of savings through accurately predicting defaulters contributing to overal profits for the banks. We use following assumption when calculating potential profits.

Assumptions:

  • Full Loan Amount was lost when a client defaults.
  • Average Loan Tenor in USA as in 2024 is 5 to 15 years (source: MoneyGeek.com). We assume 10 years loan average.
  • Average Interest Earned by Bank is around 5.60% oin 10 year loan tenor (Source: Finance Smarter), for simiplicity we will assume 5% per annum as interest rate.
  • Bank incurs on an average 1% per annum of loan value as an expense to service the loan through the period (Source: Finance Smarter).

Profit Calculation:

  • True Positive = When Machine Learning model accurately predicts the Defaulters. Contribute to Bank's Profit. Profit = Total number of correctly predicted defaulters x Avg Loan Amount for Defaults (BAD=1).
  • False Positive = When Machine Learning model incorrectly classifies a non-defaulter as defaulter, loss of revenue for bank. Loss of Earning = Total number of False Positives x 4% (interest rate (5%) less cost of servicing loan (1%)) x 10 years (Loan tenor).
  • False Negatives = When Machine Learning model misses identifying a defaulter, loss includes loan amount (Average of Loan Default value) + bank's cost (1% for 10 years).
  • True Negatives = When Machine Learning model accurately classifies non-defaulters. No change in loss or profit.

def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target, modelname, X_train=X, y_train=y, threshold=0.5):
    """
    model: classifier (from sklearn)
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    modelname: name of the model, which will be used as the index in the DataFrame
    X_train: Training data (predictors), used to calculate profit
    y_train: Training target variable (BAD), used to calculate profit
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """
    # Get predicted probabilities for class 1
    pred_prob = model.predict_proba(predictors)[:, 1]

    # Apply the threshold to get binary predictions
    pred = (pred_prob >= threshold).astype(int)

    # Calculate performance metrics
    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # F1-score
    roc = roc_auc_score(target, pred_prob)  # ROC-AUC using predicted probabilities

    # Calculate confusion matrix
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(target, pred).ravel()

    # Profit calculation logic (customized based on previous profit calculation)
    # Calculate average loan amounts based on actual y_train data
    tp_profit = X_train.loc[y_train == 1, 'LOAN'].mean()  # Average loan for defaulted loans
    avg_non_defaulted_loan = X_train.loc[y_train == 0, 'LOAN'].mean()  # Average loan for non-defaulted loans
    avg_loan_value = X_train['LOAN'].mean()  # Average loan value for all loans

    # Calculate FP cost (2% per annum for 10 years for average non-defaulted loan)
    fp_cost = avg_non_defaulted_loan * (1 + 0.02) ** 10 - avg_non_defaulted_loan

    # Calculate FN cost (average loan value + 3% operating cost for 5 years)
    fn_cost = avg_loan_value + (avg_loan_value * 0.03 * 5)

    # Set TN profit to 0 (neutral outcome)
    tn_profit = 0

    # Calculate total profit based on confusion matrix and estimated losses
    total_profit = (tp * tp_profit) - (fp * fp_cost) - (fn * fn_cost) - (tn * tn_profit)

    # Format the profit value in currency format (e.g., $30,000)
    formatted_profit = locale.currency(total_profit, grouping=True)

    # Creating a dataframe of metrics with modelname as the index, including profit
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": [acc],
            "Recall": [recall],
            "Precision": [precision],
            "F1": [f1],
            "ROC_AUC": [roc],
            "Profit": [formatted_profit] #,  # Adding profit to the performance metrics
            # "tn": [tn],
            # "fp": [fp],
            # "fn": [fn],
            # "tp": [tp],
            # "tn_profit": [tn_profit],
            # "tp_profit": [tp_profit],
            # "avg_non_defaulted_loan": [avg_non_defaulted_loan],
            # "avg_loan_value": [avg_loan_value],
            # "FP_Cost": [fp_cost],
            # "FN_Cost": [fn_cost]
        },
        index=[modelname]
    )

    return df_perf

# Provided function to plot confusion matrix
def confusion_matrix_plot(model, predictors, target, threshold=0.5):
    """
    model: classifier (from sklearn)
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    threshold: threshold for classifying the observation as class 1
    """
    # Get predicted probabilities for class 1
    y_pred_prob = model.predict_proba(predictors)[:, 1]

    # Apply the threshold to get binary predictions
    y_pred = (y_pred_prob >= threshold).astype(int)

    # Generate confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)

    # Generate labels for each cell with counts and percentages
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    # Plot confusion matrix
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="", cmap="Blues", cbar=False)
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
    plt.title(f"Confusion Matrix (Threshold = {threshold})")
    plt.show()

def find_optimum_cutoff(model, predictors, targets):
    """
    Find the optimal threshold for a given model and dataset based on Recall Score.

    Parameters:
    - model: Trained model (logistic regression, random forest, etc.)
    - predictors: Independent variables (X_test, X_train, etc.)
    - targets: True values for the dependent variable (y_test, y_train, etc.)

    Returns:
    - best_threshold: The threshold with the highest Recall Score
    - results_df: A DataFrame containing the performance metrics for different thresholds
    """
    # Generate predicted probabilities from the model
    y_prob_pred = model.predict(predictors)

    # Define threshold values to test
    thresholds = np.arange(0.1, 0.9, 0.01)

    # List to store performance results
    results = []

    for threshold in thresholds:
        # Convert probabilities to binary predictions based on the threshold
        y_pred = (y_prob_pred >= threshold).astype(int)

        # Calculate performance metrics
        accuracy = accuracy_score(targets, y_pred)
        precision = precision_score(targets, y_pred)
        recall = recall_score(targets, y_pred)
        f1 = f1_score(targets, y_pred)
        roc_auc = roc_auc_score(targets, y_prob_pred)

        # Store results for each threshold
        results.append({
            'Threshold': threshold,
            'Accuracy': accuracy,
            'Precision': precision,
            'Recall': recall,
            'F1 Score': f1,
            'ROC-AUC': roc_auc
        })

    # Convert results to a DataFrame for analysis
    results_df = pd.DataFrame(results)

    # Find the best threshold based on the highest Recall Score
    best_threshold = results_df.loc[results_df['Recall'].idxmax()]

    return best_threshold

def profit_score(y_true, y_pred, X_train, y_train):
    """
    Custom profit-based scoring function using the proposed TP, FP, FN, and TN calculations.

    Parameters:
    - y_true: True labels (BAD)
    - y_pred: Predicted labels
    - X_train: The full training dataset (predictors, including 'LOAN')
    - y_train: The target dataset (actual BAD values)

    Returns:
    - profit: Total profit/loss based on classification outcomes and estimated loss
    """
    # Calculate average loan amounts for TP, FP, and FN based on y_train (actual defaults)
    tp_profit = X_train.loc[y_train == 1, 'LOAN'].mean()  # Average loan for defaulted loans
    avg_non_defaulted_loan = X_train.loc[y_train == 0, 'LOAN'].mean()  # Average loan for non-defaulted loans
    avg_loan_value = X_train['LOAN'].mean()  # Average loan value for all loans

    # Calculate FP cost (2% per annum for 10 years for average non-defaulted loan)
    fp_cost = avg_non_defaulted_loan * (1 + 0.02) ** 10 - avg_non_defaulted_loan

    # Calculate FN cost (average loan value + 3% operating cost for 5 years)
    fn_cost = avg_loan_value + (avg_loan_value * 0.03 * 5)

    # Set TN profit to 0 (neutral outcome)
    tn_profit = 0

    # Compute confusion matrix
    tn, fp, fn, tp = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred).ravel()

    # Calculate total profit/loss based on confusion matrix and estimated losses
    total_profit = (tp * tp_profit) + (fp * fp_cost) + (fn * fn_cost) + (tn * tn_profit)

    return total_profit

# Tune hyperparameters of models using GridSearchCV.
def tune_model(model, X_train, y_train, param_grid=None, cv=5, scoring='recall'):
    """
    Parameters:
    - model: The machine learning model to tune (e.g., LogisticRegression, RandomForest, etc.)
    - X_train: Training features
    - y_train: Training labels
    - param_grid: Dictionary of hyperparameters to search. If None, a default grid is used.
    - cv: Number of cross-validation folds (default is 5)
    - scoring: Metric to optimize (default is 'recall')

    Returns:
    - best_estimator: The model with the best hyperparameters
    """
    # Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
    scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.recall_score)

    # Initialize GridSearchCV
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(model, param_grid, cv=cv, scoring=scorer)

    # Fit the GridSearchCV with training data
    grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

    # Get best estimator and best CV score
    best_estimator = grid_search.best_estimator_
    best_cv_score = grid_search.best_score_

    # Return the best estimator
    return best_estimator, best_cv_score

# Create a custom scorer using make_scorer
custom_profit_scorer = make_scorer(
    profit_score,
    greater_is_better=True,
    X_train=X_train,  # Pass the predictors
    y_train=y_train   # Pass the target variable
)

  • The LDA - Original model demonstrates low Recall (36.93%) and moderate Precision (57.58%) on the Training set, leading to a negative Profit (-\$6,170,986.31). The performance on the Validation set is similar, with low Recall (34.21%) and Precision (52.00%), resulting in another negative Profit (-$1,766,368.52). This indicates that the original LDA model struggles to identify defaulters, with poor profitability on both the training and validation sets.

  • The LDA - Oversampled model improves significantly on the Training set, with Recall (80.45%) and Precision (67.45%), resulting in a strong Profit (\$23,285,278.60). On the Validation set, although Recall remains high (76.32%), Precision drops to 32.22%, leading to a lower but positive Profit ($222,875.12). This model demonstrates better generalization compared to the original model, although the drop in Precision suggests a higher rate of False Positives on unseen data.

  • The LDA - Tuned model shows slightly improved Recall (40.08%) and Precision (54.66%) on the Training set, but still results in a negative Profit (-\$5,463,133.43). On the Validation set, Recall (36.84%) and Precision (51.47%) remain low, leading to a negative Profit (-$1,604,425.13). The tuning improves the balance between Recall and Precision slightly but fails to bring the model to profitability.

  • The LDA - Oversampled Tuned model performs identically to the oversampled model on both the Training set and Validation set. It achieves high Recall (80.45%) and Precision (67.45%) on the Training set, leading to a high Profit (\$23,285,278.60). On the Validation set, Recall remains at 76.32%, but Precision drops to 32.22%, leading to a more moderate Profit ($222,875.12). This suggests that the tuning did not further improve the oversampled models performance, which already performed well.

Recommendation: The LDA - Oversampled (Validation) model provides the best overall performance, with high Recall (76.32%) and a positive Profit ($222,875.12) on the validation set, indicating better generalization compared to the original and tuned models. The Oversampled Tuned model shows identical results, so further tuning did not yield any additional benefits. Both oversampled models perform significantly better than the original LDA models, which struggled with both Recall and profitability.

The model delivers a high Profit on the training set (\$5,035,109.78) and reasonable validation results ($859,040.48), with a trade-off between Recall and Precision.

  • The Random Forest Oversampled model shows a significant improvement in Precision on the training set (77.32%), while maintaining high Recall (91.91%). However, on the Validation set, Recall drops (72.11%), with lower Precision (39.59%). The training profit is quite large (\$37,780,020.73), but the validation profit is much smaller ($312,758.21), suggesting potential overfitting on the oversampled data.

  • The Tuned Random Forest model with oversampling has the highest training profit (\$35,423,029.36) but shows weaker **validation performance** (Recall: 73.16%, Precision: 35.10%) and a lower **profit** ($193,345.07), which again suggests possible overfitting and reduced generalizability when applied to unseen data.

  • Recommendation: Among the Random Forest models, the Random Forest (Validation) model provides a better balance between Recall, Precision, and Profit on the validation set ($859,040.48), indicating it might generalize better. While the oversampled models show higher training performance, their validation results suggest overfitting, making the original Random Forest model a better choice.

We will continue by evaluating other models, next being Gradient Boosting models, to further optimize Recall, Precision, and Profit and compare their performance to Random Forest and Logistic Regression models.

ADA Boost (Validation) 0.199161 1.000000 0.199161 0.332168 0.802222 $44,463.20
ADA Boost Oversampled (Train) 0.500000 1.000000 0.500000 0.666667 0.921568 $37,969,700.88
ADA Boost Oversampled (Validation) 0.199161 1.000000 0.199161 0.332168 0.784100 $44,463.20
Tuned ADA Boost (Train) 0.398270 1.000000 0.249018 0.398742 0.962028 $3,268,209.65

Tuned ADA Boost Oversampled (Train) 0.566656 1.000000 0.535708 0.697669 0.976247 $39,613,681.77
Tuned ADA Boost Oversampled (Validation) 0.287212 0.973684 0.215116 0.352381 0.846149 $217,778.82

Observations:

  • The ADA Boost (Train) model achieves perfect Recall (100%), meaning it identifies all defaulters. However, Precision is extremely low (19.95%), indicating that many non-defaulters are misclassified as defaulters. This results in a low F1 score (33.27%) and a modest Profit (\$206,446.71). On the Validation set, the performance is similar, with 100% Recall but very low Precision (19.92%), leading to a smaller Profit ($44,463.20). The model heavily favors identifying defaulters at the expense of misclassifying non-defaulters.

  • The ADA Boost Oversampled model improves Precision (50%) on the Training set, while maintaining perfect Recall (100%). This results in a higher F1 score (66.67%) and significantly higher Profit (\$37,969,700.88). However, on the Validation set, the performance reverts to the original model, with 100% Recall and low Precision (19.92%), resulting in a smaller Profit ($44,463.20). This suggests the model is overfitting to the oversampled training data.

  • The Tuned ADA Boost (Train) model maintains perfect Recall (100%) but slightly improves Precision (24.90%), resulting in a higher F1 score (39.87%) and a better Profit (\$3,268,209.65) on the Training set. On the Validation set, Recall remains high (97.89%), with a slight increase in Precision (24.09%), leading to a much improved Profit ($614,509.21). This tuned version demonstrates better generalization compared to the original ADA Boost model.

  • The Tuned ADA Boost Oversampled model achieves perfect Recall (100%) and significantly improved Precision (53.57%) on the Training set, resulting in a high F1 score (69.77%) and Profit (\$39,613,681.77). On the Validation set, while Recall remains high (97.37%), Precision drops significantly (21.51%), resulting in a lower Profit ($217,778.82). This indicates that the model is overfitting to the oversampled data and struggling to generalize.

  • Recommendation: Among the ADA Boost models, the Tuned ADA Boost (Validation) model provides the best balance between Recall (97.89%), Precision (24.09%), and Profit ($614,509.21). While the oversampled models perform well on the training set, they show signs of overfitting with significantly lower performance on the validation set, making the Tuned ADA Boost a more reliable option for deployment.

Observations:

  • The XGBoost (Train) model achieves perfect Recall and Precision (100%), leading to a perfect F1-score (100%) and high training Profit (\$12,538,323.04). However, on the Validation set, Recall drops to 60.53% with high Precision (87.79%), resulting in a solid Profit ($273,148.88). This indicates the model is overfitted to the training data but still maintains reasonable performance on the validation set.

  • The XGBoost Oversampled model performs excellently on the Training set, with Recall (99.93%) and Precision (100%), generating a very high Profit (\$50,227,105.62). On the Validation set, Recall (67.89%) and Precision (84.87%) improve over the non-oversampled model, yielding a significantly higher Profit ($766,175.16). This suggests better generalization with oversampling, although some degree of overfitting remains.

  • The Tuned XGBoost (Train) model improves Recall (90.67%), but Precision drops to 42.57%, leading to a Profit (\$6,134,025.81) on the training set. On the Validation set, Recall improves to 78.42%, but Precision remains low at 36.08%, resulting in a moderate Profit ($537,428.16). This model shows a trade-off, prioritizing Recall over Precision, but the validation results suggest reduced performance in correctly identifying non-defaulters.

  • The Tuned XGBoost Oversampled model achieves perfect performance on the Training set with 100% Recall and Precision, leading to a very high training Profit (\$37,973,740.14). However, on the Validation set, while Recall remains perfect (100%), Precision drops drastically to 19.92%, resulting in a low Profit ($44,463.20). This indicates severe overfitting to the training data, with very poor generalization on unseen data.

  • Recommendation: Among the XGBoost models, the XGBoost Oversampled (Validation) model provides the best balance between Recall (67.89%), Precision (84.87%), and Profit ($766,175.16). While the model shows some overfitting, it generalizes better than the non-oversampled and tuned models. The Tuned XGBoost models, especially the oversampled version, suffer from overfitting, with a significant drop in Precision and reduced profitability on the validation set, making them less ideal for production.

Selected Models and Reasons:¶

  5. Logistic Regression Tuned on Scaled Data (Seq 5):

    • Similar to the scaled version, this model shows low overfitting and Recall (76%) with stable Profit ($202,679), making it another reliable choice for deployment.

Insights and Recommendations¶

Key insights indicate that the Random Forest model tuned on oversampled data effectively predicts loan defaults, balancing recall and precision. Continuous refinement and exploring additional algorithms are recommended for improved performance and adaptability.

  • Key Insights
  • Business Recommendations

Key Insights:¶

  • Objective Alignment: The machine learning model effectively predicts loan defaults, automating the banks decision-making process and reducing bias in loan approvals.
  • Top Features: Key features like DELINQ (30.17% importance), CLAGE (15.29%), and DEROG (12.45%) are the most influential in predicting loan defaults, emphasizing the borrowers credit history.
  • Model Performance: Random Forest built on original data showed the best overall performance, with high Recall (81%) and the highest profit ($779K), indicating its effectiveness in identifying defaulters while ensuring profitability.
  • Profit Calculation: The profit model aligns well with the banks objectives by calculating savings from correctly predicted defaulters (True Positives) and potential lost revenue due to misclassified non-defaulters (False Positives).
  • EDA Findings: Higher loan amounts, mortgage dues, and debt-to-income ratios are linked to higher default risk, highlighting key risk factors.
  • Balanced Precision: The model maintains moderate Precision (34.71%) with a balanced F1 score, indicating the model captures defaulters well while managing a reasonable level of false positives.
  • Interpretability: Features like loan amount, debt-to-income ratio, and derogatory reports provide clear insights into default risks, ensuring the model remains interpretable.
  • Low Overfitting: The selected model shows consistent performance across training, validation, and test sets, confirming good generalization to unseen data.
  • Loan Default Impact: The impact of loan defaults on profitability is significant, making the prediction of defaults critical for financial stability.
  • Business Objective Alignment: The selected model supports the banks goals of reducing non-performing assets (NPA) while complying with regulatory standards like ECOA.

Business Recommendations and Next Steps:¶

  • Deploy Random Forest Model: Deploy the Random Forest model built on original data for production. It strikes the best balance between high Recall, profitability, and low overfitting, ensuring effective loan default prediction.
  • Focus on Top Features: Use key features like delinquent credit lines, age of credit lines, and derogatory reports to refine loan approval criteria and mitigate default risk.
  • Monitor Model Performance: Regularly track model performance in production, particularly Recall and Precision, to ensure consistent default prediction and minimize loan losses.
  • Profit Calculation Review: Continuously review and refine the profit calculation to ensure it reflects current interest rates, loan servicing costs, and default recovery strategies.
  • Improve Loan Risk Assessment: Integrate the model into the banks loan underwriting process, automating decisions and reducing reliance on manual, error-prone evaluations.
  • Data Refresh: Regularly update the model with new data to ensure accuracy and adaptability to changing market conditions and borrower profiles.
  • Compliance and Interpretability: Ensure the model remains interpretable and transparent, in line with regulatory guidelines like the Equal Credit Opportunity Act (ECOA).
  • Test on New Data: Further validate the model on additional datasets to ensure robust generalization before full deployment.
  • Enhance Client Engagement: Use insights from the model to offer better financial advice to clients, helping them improve creditworthiness and avoid default.
  • Refine Risk Mitigation Strategy: Incorporate the models results into broader risk mitigation strategies, enabling the bank to set more informed loan approval policies.

These key insights and recommendations will guide the deployment and management of the predictive model in line with the banks objectives and operational needs.
